"Ohtaka A., Nishino M., Kobayashi T.","Disappearance of deep profundal zoobenthos in Lake Ikeda, southern Kyushu, Japan, with relation to recent environmental changes in the lake",2006,"Limnology","7","3",,"237","242",,,10.1007/s10201-006-0180-2,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33845483484&partnerID=40&md5=a87019dc98e7f7702b6336a28bc5f092","Department of Natural Science, Faculty of Education, Hirosaki University, Hirosaki, Aomori 036-8560, Japan; Lake Biwa Environmental Research Institute, Shiga, Japan; Institute for Environmental and Social Welfare Studies, Kawasaki, Japan","Ohtaka, A., Department of Natural Science, Faculty of Education, Hirosaki University, Hirosaki, Aomori 036-8560, Japan; Nishino, M., Lake Biwa Environmental Research Institute, Shiga, Japan; Kobayashi, T., Institute for Environmental and Social Welfare Studies, Kawasaki, Japan","A benthological survey in a deep caldera, Lake Ikeda, southern Kyushu, Japan, in 1998 revealed that no zoobenthos were found in the deep profundal, although two tubificid oligochaetes, Tubifex tubifex and Limnodrilus hoffmeisteri, and a chironomid, Procladius sp., were distributed in the upper profundal zone. This is the first record of oligochaete composition in the lake. Lake Ikeda had been typically oligotrophic until the 1940s, and zoobenthic assemblages were recorded throughout the profundal bottom in the 1920s and 1970s. Recent disappearance of the deep profundal zoobenthos could be caused by the stagnation of anoxic waters in the hypolimnion, in connection with eutrophication triggered by nutrient loading, as well as change in the thermal circulation system presumably caused by global warming. © The Japanese Society of Limnology 2006.","Azoic zone; Eutrophication; Global warming; Lake Ikeda; Oligochaetes; Zoobenthos","anoxic conditions; environmental change; eutrophication; global warming; hypolimnion; oligotrophic environment; temperature effect; zoobenthos; Asia; Eurasia; Far East; Japan; Kagoshima [Kyushu]; Kyushu; Lake Ikeda; Annelida; Chironomidae; Limnodrilus hoffmeisteri; Oligochaeta (Metazoa); Procladius; Tubifex tubifex; Tubificidae",,,,,,"Arai, T., Global warming and the temperature of inland waters (2000) Jpn J Limnol, 61, pp. 24-34. , (in Japanese with English abstract); Aston, R.J., Tubificids and water quality: A review (1973) Environ Pollut, 5, pp. 1-10; Blumberg, A.F., Di Toro, D.M., Effect of climate warming on dissolved oxygen concentration in Lake Erie (1990) Trans Am Fish Soc, 119, pp. 210-233; Brinkhurst, R.O., The fauna of pollution (1969) The Great Lakes As an Environment, , In: Great Lakes Institute, University of Toronto, Toronoto, Ontario; Brinkhurst, R.O., (1974) The Benthos of Lakes, , Macmillan Press, London; Brinkhurst, R.O., Kennedy, C.R., Studies on the biology of the Tubificidae (Annelida, Oligochaeta) in a polluted stream (1965) J Anim Ecol, 34, pp. 429-443; Dermott, R.M., Zoobenthic distribution and biomass in the Turkey lakes (1988) Can J Fish Aquat Sci, 45, pp. 107-114; Endoh, S., Yamashita, S., Kawakami, I., Okumura, Y., Recent warming of Lake Biwa water (1999) Jpn J Limnol, 60, pp. 223-228; Fend, S.V., Ohtaka, A., Yamaguchia toyensis n. sp., n. gen. (Annelida, Citellata, Lubriculidae) from profundal lake habitat in Japan (2004) Zool Sci, 21, pp. 677-683; Hirae, T., Water quality and lake environmental conditions in Lake Ikeda (2000) Res Rep Natl Inst Environ Stud Jpn, 153, pp. 242-249. , (in Japanese); Ishida, T., Eucyclops pacificus and E. ohtakai, two new cyclopoid copepods (Crustacea) from Japan (2000) Biogeography, 2, pp. 21-28; Kennedy, C.R., The life history of Limnodrilus hoffmeisteri (Oligochaeta: Tubificidae) and its adaptive significance (1966) Oikos, 17, pp. 158-168; Kitagawa, N., A classification of Japanese lakes based on hypolimnetic oxygen and benthonic fauna (1978) Jpn J Limnol, 39, pp. 1-8. , (in Japanese with English abstract); Kitagawa, N., Studies on the bottom fauna of four lakes in southern Kyus